[normal]Number of memberships terminated in 2013[bold]&#xa0;[bold]NAPIT Registration’s
[normal] disciplinary process is set up with a number of sanctions such that non
[normal]‐
[normal]compliance does not simply result in termination (not least because that would result in successful appeals and legal challenges if opportunities to address non
[normal]‐
[normal]compliance are not giv
[normal]en). Non
[normal]‐
[normal]compliance is against any of the requirements of the EAS which may mean that non
[normal]‐
[normal]compliance is against the rules allowing self
[normal]‐
[normal]certification even if works are compliant with the Building Regulations. 
[normal]In 2013, the following compliance actions and 
[normal]sanctions were taken: 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Hence the 163 who cance
[normal]lled their own membership without addressing improvement actions plus the 2
[normal]4
[normal] actively removed by the compliance procedure gives 18
[normal]7
[normal] whose membership ended as a result of identified non
[normal]‐
[normal]compliance.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This figure represents 15% of the 1224 enterprises whose P
[normal]art P membership ended during 2013 the remaining 85% is made up of retirements, business closure, sole traders gaining employment in larger firms and simple non
[normal]‐
[normal]renewal. Only a small number of these seem to have scheme
[normal]‐
[normal]hopped, the majority are either genui
[normal]nely not trading or they continue to trade without being registered.
